      <akn:section eId="sec_28:2_204">
        <akn:num>28:2-204</akn:num>
        <akn:heading>Formation in general.</akn:heading>
<akn:subsection eId="subsec_28:2-204_1">
      <akn:num>(1)</akn:num>
      <akn:content><akn:p>A contract for sale of goods may be made in any manner sufficient to show agreement, including conduct by both parties which recognizes the existence of such a contract.</akn:p></akn:content>
    </akn:subsection><akn:subsection eId="subsec_28:2-204_2">
      <akn:num>(2)</akn:num>
      <akn:content><akn:p>An agreement sufficient to constitute a contract for sale may be found even though the moment of its making is undetermined.</akn:p></akn:content>
    </akn:subsection><akn:subsection eId="subsec_28:2-204_3">
      <akn:num>(3)</akn:num>
      <akn:content><akn:p>Even though one or more terms are left open a contract for sale does not fail for indefiniteness if the parties have intended to make a contract and there is a reasonably certain basis for giving an appropriate remedy.</akn:p></akn:content>
    </akn:subsection>
      </akn:section>
